Yes, and he&#x27;s said that in a few blog posts as well:<p><a href="http://herbsutter.com/2013/06/07/gotw-92-solution-auto-variables-part-1/" rel="nofollow">http://herbsutter.com/2013/06/07/gotw-92-solution-auto-varia...</a><p><a href="http://herbsutter.com/2013/06/07/gotw-93-auto-variables-part-2/" rel="nofollow">http://herbsutter.com/2013/06/07/gotw-93-auto-variables-part...</a><p><a href="http://herbsutter.com/2013/08/12/gotw-94-solution-aaa-style-almost-always-auto/" rel="nofollow">http://herbsutter.com/2013/08/12/gotw-94-solution-aaa-style-...</a><p>He has some good points, but his perspective seems to be biased by a professional focus on writing libraries and more general-purpose code. He&#x27;s also brilliant and can remember things like this:<p><pre><code>  const int&  cir = val;
  auto        h   = cir;
  //The type of h is int.
</code></pre>
It&#x27;s difficult to make generic rules for how to use C++ (because it&#x27;s used for everything from adware to nuclear reactors), but I can say that Herb&#x27;s AAA (Almost Always Auto) rule would not fly on any development team I&#x27;ve ever worked with.
